Difference between DELETE, TRUNCATE, DROP.\
"DELETE is a DML (Data Manipulation Language) command — it removes specific rows from a table based on a WHERE condition. If I don't specify a WHERE clause, it deletes all rows
, but the table structure remains intact.

TRUNCATE is a DDL (Data Definition Language) command — it removes ALL rows from a table at once, but keeps the table structure intact. 
Unlike DELETE, I can't use a WHERE clause with TRUNCATE — it always removes everything

DROP is also a DDL command, but it's the most destructive — it removes the ENTIRE table, including its structure, data, indexes, and constraints.
After DROP, the table no longer exists in the database at all

What are Stored Procedures?
A Stored Procedure is a precompiled set of SQL statements stored in the database, which I can call by name whenever I need to execute that logic — 
instead of writing and sending raw SQL queries from the application every time
Stored Procedures are precompiled and their execution plan is cached by the database, so repeated calls execute faster compared to sending raw ad-hoc SQL queries every time.
Business logic involving complex queries can be centralized in the database — multiple applications or services can call the same stored procedure instead of duplicating the same SQL logic in different codebases


